th/MathML\" alttext=\"y equals four ninths x minus one third\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>4</mn><mn>9</mn></mfrac><mi>x</mi><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></math>. Therefore, the slope of line <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"r\"><mi>r</mi></math> is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"four ninths\"><mfrac><mn>4</mn><mn>9</mn></mfrac></math>. Since parallel lines have equal slopes, the slope of line <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"s\"><mi>s</mi></math> is also <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"four ninths\"><mfrac><mn>4</mn><mn>9</mn></mfrac></math>.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Choice A is incorrect. This is the reciprocal of the slope of line <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"s\"><mi>s</mi></math>, not the slope of line <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"s\"><mi>s</mi></math>.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Choice C is incorrect and may result from conceptual or calculation errors.&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Choice D is incorrect and may result from conceptual or calculation errors.&nbsp;</p>",
